SIMPLE: grit
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Grit
<hw>Grit</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE, <ets>greet</ets>,
<ets>greot</ets>, sand, gravel, AS. <ets>gre⟦oacute⟧t</ets> grit, sant,
dust; akin to OS <ets>griott</ets>, OFries. <ets>gret</ets> gravel, OHG.
<ets>grioz</ets>, G. <ets>griess</ets>, Icel. <ets>grj⟦omac⟧t</ets>, and
to E. <ets>groats</ets>, <ets>grout</ets>. See <er>Groats</er>,
<er>Grout</er>, and cf. <er>Grail</er> gravel.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Sand or gravel; rough, hard particles.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The coarse part of meal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 652 --></p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Grain, esp. oats or wheat, hulled
and coarsely ground; in high milling, fragments of cracked wheat smaller
than groats.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>A hard, coarse-grained siliceous
sandstone; <as>as, millstone <ex>grit</ex></as>; -- called also
<altname>gritrock</altname> and <altname>gritstone.</altname> The name
is also applied to a finer sharp-grained sandstone; <as>as, grindstone
<ex>grit</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Structure, as adapted to grind or sharpen; <as>as, a
hone of good <ex>grit</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Firmness of mind; invincible spirit; unyielding
courage; fortitude.</def> <rj><au>C. Reade.</au> <au>E. P.
Whipple.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Grit
<hw>Grit</hw> <pr>(gr⟦icr⟧t)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To give forth a
grating sound, as sand under the feet; to grate; to grind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sanded floor that <qex>grits</qex> beneath the tread.</q>
<rj><qau>Goldsmith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Grit
<hw>Grit</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Gritted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Gritting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To grind; to rub harshly
together; to grate; <as>as, to grit the teeth</as>.</def>
<mark>[Collog.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grith</ent>⟦br⟧
